name: tetraethyl 2,2'-(benzene-1,3-diyldiimino)dipropanedioate
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-3121
Reason: 1,3-Benzenediimine (1,3-diaza-2,4-diene) has a melting point around -10°C. The presence of two propanedioate groups (O=C(OCC)C(=O)OCC) increases the molecular weight and introduces polar carbonyl interactions, which can significantly increase the melting point due to hydrogen bonding and dipole-dipole interactions, adding approximately +100°C. The tetraethyl substitution increases the molecular volume and steric hindrance, which can lower the melting point due to a less compact crystal lattice, reducing it by approximately -20°C. Summing these modifications: 1,3-Benzenediimine base (-10°C), two propanedioate groups (+100°C), and tetraethyl substitution (-20°C).
